snippet.textDisplay:
Sorry to say that this song didn’t seem like the standard type creations we get from coke studio bangla.
It is obvious that the lyrics and type of singing is unique. Despite the fact, if you scroll YouTube randomly, you will find music which is of a kinda similar standard. I don’t disrespecting the music or the musician, but i am being a bit critical. Maybe its because we expect more from coke studio bangla.
Some advice I wanna share.
01. Don't rush. This song came comparatively faster. More effort, more brainstorming is suggested.
02. People loved songs from different dialects. That's true. Don't take it as a trend. 
03. You have already introduced rap in 3-4 songs. Try to include something different.
04. If you have a story behind, it will be more great. People love stories. Like murir tin.

I was being honest. Maybe my opinion will differ from others. Wishing coke studio bangla luck for the next creation. 
❤❤❤❤❤❤❤❤❤

snippet.textDisplay: Is there no other artist in Bangladesh? Coke Studio BD introduced this artist with the other tribal language in the previous season, and it was absolutely fantastic; we got it. But why is it happening again? We have many talented artists, not just Animes, and Coke Studio is all about creating and experimenting with different song compositions, not repeating the same thing! I'm not sure what's wrong with Arnab!

snippet.textDisplay: It is really a great surprise to get such a song from ❝Coke Studio Bangla❞. I really did not expect to see such an energetic performance. Absolutely goosebumps! Many thanks to Animes Da for presenting his own culture ❝Hajong❞ beautifully in front of the entire people of Bengal. Animesh Da, your first identity is that you are a Bangladeshi. Many thanks and heartfelt love for highlighting the ❝Hajong❞ culture through such a rock song. Go ahead bro, lots of love and best wishes for you from Mirpur, Dhaka ❤️🇧🇩
